        </span>
        <Sparkle class="absolute right-8 top-10 h-4 w-4 text-[var(--color-coral-300)] blob-drift" />
        <Sparkle class="absolute left-9 bottom-20 h-3.5 w-3.5 text-[var(--color-mint-300)] blob-drift-slow" />

        <p class="relative mt-5 text-xs font-bold uppercase text-white/60" style="letter-spacing: 0.08em;">AVS Licensed Pet Shop</p>
        <p class="relative mt-2 font-[family-name:var(--font-heading)] text-2xl font-bold text-white">{site.license.number}</p>
        <p class="relative mt-3 text-sm leading-relaxed text-white/75">
          Search this number on the public registry to confirm it yourself, any time.
        </p>
        <a
          href={site.license.registryUrl}
          class="clay-btn relative mt-6 inline-flex w-full items-center justify-center gap-2 bg-[var(--color-accent)] px-5 py-3 text-sm font-bold text-white hover:bg-[var(--color-accent-hover)]"
        >
          <PawPrint class="h-4 w-4" />
          Verify on AVS registry
        </a>
      </div>
      <p>
        Curious Tails is AVS-licensed under pet shop licence AS24J00046. You can check this yourself, in under a minute, on the{' '}
        <a href={site.license.registryUrl} class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">AVS public registry</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        This matters because not every seller in Singapore is licensed. Puppies from unlicensed sources are often{' '}
        <a href="https://www.ica.gov.sg/news-and-publications/newsroom/media-release/33-per-cent-decrease-in-animal-smuggling-cases-recorded-in-2025" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">smuggled in from across the border</a>,
        without health checks or proper vaccination, and are often listed on Carousell or Telegram by an unlicensed pet seller. Puppies have died from canine parvovirus after being smuggled, and{' '}
        <a href="https://spca.org.sg/campaigns/animal-smuggling/" class="underline underline-offset-2 text-[var(--color-accent-hover)]">welfare groups like the SPCA</a>{' '}
        have campaigned against it for years.
      </p>
      <p>If a seller can't show you a licence number you can verify on the public registry, that's worth pausing on. An honest pet shop will have one; a genuine puppy seller won't mind you checking.</p>
